<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-340  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 340.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Jan 31 1990 n1354* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Ericsson writes its telecommunications management software in C++to X/Open standards. (LM Ericsson Telefon AB) (productannouncement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   L.M. Ericsson Telefon AB (product introduction).andO;Product:   C++ (Program development software) (usage)Telecommunications Management and Operations Support (Networkmanagement software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionTelecommunicationsNetwork Management SoftwareUNIXX Windows (Standard).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>ERICSSON WRITES ITS TELECOMMUNICATIONS MANAGEMENTandM;SOFTWARE IN C++ TO X/OPEN STANDARDSandM;As the spearhead of its public telecommunications offerings for the 1990s, LM Ericsson Telefon AB has launched a new set of computerised management andoperations support systems designed for multiple hardware-based publictelecommunications networks.andP;  According to the announcement, the systems,which conform to the CCITT/ANSI Telecommunications Management Networkstandards, are aimed at management of five specific areas in a publicnetwork: the switching network, transport network, intelligent networkservices, business services such as virtual private networks, and cellularmobile telephone networks.andP;  Marketed under the collective name of TMOS -Telecommunications Management and Operations Support - they run in a Unixenvironment specified by the customer - Sun Microsystems' Unix was cited asone possible choice - with a Sybase object-oriented relational database atthe centre of each system.andP;  The C++ programming language is used, and eachsystem conforms to the X/Open Common Applications Environment standards forsoftware compatibility; applications specific to each of the five areasmentioned above are in-house developed by Ericsson.andP;  The NMAS NetworkManagement System handles fault administration, traffic management and calldata connection within the switching network; the SMAS Service ManagementSystem is aimed at the design and introduction into the network ofintelligent network services such as freephone and credit card validation;the FMAS Facilities Management System is designed to manage the transportnetwork, including Digital Cross Connect systems used for digital leasedlines, video traffic switching and network configuration; the CMAS CellularManagement System addresses the cellular mobile telephone network, and theBMAS Business Management System helps individual business users to accessnetwork management tools directly, and control their own use of networkservices.andP;  Ericsson claims that the modular design of the five systemsenables the user to implement only those features required; and each systemcan be used by itself or in conjunction with any of the others by using thedatabase, which contains a &quot;picture&quot; of the entire network, as a sharedresource.andP;  Ericsson says the new systems will respond to the increasingdesire expressed by telecommunications administrations to &quot;add value&quot; totheir services; orders have already been received from Finland and Italy, andEricsson is particularly proud of a contract from one of Ameritech'ssubsidiaries, Illinois Bell.andP;  Ameritech will be using the SMAS system toprovide centralised management of a service-independent &quot;intelligent&quot; networkplanned to be up and running in Chicago by early 1991.andO;</TEXT></DOC>